      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Changing Face of Harlem</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Yvonne V Jones letter on series on life on 129th St in Harlem; holds while improvements will spur return of middle class to Harlem, it is dismaying that majority of workers employed in renovation of buildings are not African-Americans</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An American Block: Life on 129th Street'' (front page, Feb. 18, 19 and 21):</p>
        <p>Though the renovation of brownstones and apartment complexes will indeed bring back the middle class to Harlem, it is dismaying that the vast majority of workers employed in the renovation of the buildings are not African-Americans.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An American Block: Life on 129th Street'' (front page, Feb. 18, 19 and 21):</p>
        <p>Though the renovation of brownstones and apartment complexes will indeed bring back the middle class to Harlem, it is dismaying that the vast majority of workers employed in the renovation of the buildings are not African-Americans.</p>
        <p>The construction industry has long been a bastion of employment for working-class white men. Contractors perpetuate the myth that the skills they look for in workers are so specialized as not to be found in the general population. But TV shows and Web sites are demystifying the home-renovation process.</p>
        <p>Until renovation and construction involve Harlem residents, 129th Street will be aesthetically attractive, but Central Harlem will remain structurally unchanged.</p>
        <p>YVONNE V. JONES  Louisville, Ky., Feb. 21, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is an associate professor of anthropology at the University of Louisville.</p>
      </block>
